d many of the larger guilds willing to go along. And unfortunately - as hard as it is to admit it - as the large guilds go, so goes the server. If the top 10 guilds united in something like this and made it a server wide event to include everyone, there wouldn't be near the fall out.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> However, when a guild who is more like 20 or so decides to take it upon themselves, it upsets people who have worked long and hard to see Xev be a civil server. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Odd sort of logic here.  Let me point out some logical fallacies in this line of logic.<br>
<br>
10 top guilds saying okay = we can wake sleeper cuz 10 guilds say so, but one cannot?  /boggle  This by definition is considered a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Converse Accident</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
Definition:  An exception to a generalization is applied to cases where the generalization should apply.<br>
<br>
Examples: <br>
(i) Because we allow terminally ill patients to use heroin, we<br>
should allow everyone to use heroin.<br>
(ii) Because you allowed Jill, who was hit by a truck, to<br>
hand in her assignment late, you should allow the entire<br>
class to hand in their assignments late.<br>
(iii) Because ten guilds decide to make an agreement, the agreement now applies to everyone.<br>
<br>
Proof: <br>
Identify the generalization in question and show how the<br>
special case was an exception to the generalization.<br>
<br>
10 top guilds can dictate when to use sleeper script, but one cannot? This is called <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Straw Man</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
Definition: <br>
The author attacks an argument which is different from, and<br>
usually weaker than, the opposition's best argument.<br>
<br>
Examples: <br>
(i) We should have conscription. People don't want to enter<br>
the military because they find it an inconvenience. But they<br>
should realize that there are more important things than<br>
convenience. <br>
<br>
(ii) We should have Serverwide event dictated by 10 top guilds to wake sleeper. Non-guilded players and lower end guilds don't want Sleeper woken because they find it an inconvenience. But they should realize that there are more important things than convenience. <br>
<br>
Proof: <br>
Show that the opposition's argument has been<br>
misrepresented by showing that the opposition has a stronger<br>
argument. Describe the stronger argument.<br>
<br>
Where was the 10 top guilds initiative to this decision to make it a server event?  3 yrs is a hell of long time to fail to show it.  Probably because you were never going to do it.  Why?  Same reason Hawkestone is getting flamed now, cuz we did it.<br>
This is called <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Begging the Question</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> ( petitio principii )<br>
<br>
Definition:<br>
The truth of the conclusion is assumed by the premises.<br>
Often, the conclusion is simply restated in the premises in a<br>
slightly different form. In more difficult cases, the premise is<br>
a consequence of the conclusion.<br>
<br>
Examples: <br>
(i) Since I'm not lying, it follows that I'm telling the truth.<br>
<br>
(ii) Since we could have formed a serverwide coalition to sleeper, it follows that we would have done it.<br>
<br>
Proof: <br>
Show that in order to believe that the premises are true we<br>
must already agree that the conclusion is true.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think a lot of the major guilds who had been through ST (mine included) were aware that the agreement was a bit outdated with the revamping of ST. I think many (mine included) don't even really mind that the sleeper was woken. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is known as <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Equivocation</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
Definition:<br>
The same word is used with two different meanings.<br>
<br>
Examples: <br>
(i) Criminal actions are illegal, and all murder trials are<br>
criminal actions, thus all murder trials are illegal. (Here the<br>
term &quot;criminal actions&quot; is used with two different meanings.<br>
Example borrowed from Copi.)<br>
(ii) A few select ST capable guilds agreed to an pact to not wake sleeper, and sleeper cannot be woken by those ST capable guilds, thus a pact agreeing guild did not kill sleeper.<br>
<br>
Proof:<br>
Identify the word which is used twice, then show that a<br>
definition which is appropriate for one use of the word would<br>
not be appropriate for the second use.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Had Hawkestone asked before doing it - they might have found many of the larger guilds willing to go along. And unfortunately - as hard as it is to admit it - as the large guilds go, so goes the server. If the top 10 guilds united in something like this and made it a server wide event to include everyone, there wouldn't be near the fall out<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Odd, so Hawkestone + larger guilds = okay to wake sleeper and follow script, but not near the razing Hawkestone is getting now?  This is called <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Inconsistency</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
<br>
Definition: <br>
The author asserts more than one proposition such that the<br>
propositions cannot all be true. In such a case, the<br>
propositions may be contradictories or they may be<br>
contraries.<br>
<br>
Examples: <br>
(i) Montreal is about 200 km from Ottawa, while Toronto is<br>
400 km from Ottawa. Toronto is closer to Ottawa than<br>
Montreal.<br>
(ii) Hawkestone approaches larger guilds about waking sleeper, Hawkestone and larger guilds wake sleeper with little or no flak from xev.  Hawkestone wakes sleeper by itself = lots of flak from xev player base.<br>
<br>
Proof: <br>
Assume that one of the statements is true, and then use it as<br>
a premise to show that one of the other statements is false.<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :banghead --><img src=http://216.40.249.192/s/contrib/ruinkai/smashfreakB.gif ALT=":banghead"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
Logic is your friend, try it some time.<br>
<br>
<br>
Sir Maverickpoet Mistcallerbane<br>
65 Paladin of Tunare<br>
Proud member of Hawkestone<br>
